Wilson says Davis ignored warnings about energy=20
Former governor defends himself=20
Carla Marinucci, Chronicle Political Writer=20
<mailto:cmarinucci@sfchronicle.com>
Friday, July 20, 2001=20
,2001 San Francisco Chronicle </chronicle/info/copyright>=20
URL:=20
<http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=3D/chronicle/archive/2001/0=
7/20/
MN187903.DTL>
Former Gov. Pete Wilson, who signed the controversial 1996 energy=20
deregulation bill into law, blasted his successor Gray Davis yesterday for=
=20
failing to aggressively use the governor's most forceful tool -- emergency=
=20
powers -- to contain the state's energy crisis.=20
"There are people who have ignored the supply and tried to blame the crisis=
=20
on everyone else," the Republican former governor told nearly 100 academics=
=20
and reporters at the Public Policy Institute in San Francisco yesterday.=20
Arguing that Davis ignored early warnings about brewing problems and "put i=
n=20
jeopardy parks, schools and other capital needs," Wilson said the Democrati=
c=20
governor has skillfully engaged in finger-pointing and public relations to=
=20
blur perception of the current energy troubles.=20
"They've sought to blame me, and have done so with some success. . . . And=
=20
they've found a much more profitable and exciting target, President Bush,"=
=20
said Wilson, who wryly pronounced Bush's recent trip to California as "a=20
triumph -- for Davis."=20
But Davis' strategy, he said, "doesn't create one watt of new power."=20
Wilson's speech -- his toughest public remarks to date on the energy crisis=
=20
-- came the day the Public Policy Institute, a nonpartisan think tank,=20
released polls showing Californians now believe energy ranks far and away a=
s=20
the state's most pressing problem. Many of those voters blame Wilson, not=
=20
Davis, for the power shortages and rolling blackouts, the poll shows.=20
The former governor's sharp words were rejected by Davis' senior political=
=20
adviser, Garry South, who said Wilson is trying to "revise history."=20
"If there is one shred of evidence that Pete Wilson said one thing or raise=
d=20
one red flag about energy supply, let him produce it," South said yesterday=
.=20
"Pete Wilson accusing Gov. Davis of being responsible (for energy) is like=
=20
Herbert Hoover blaming FDR for the Depression. We're trying to clean up his=
=20
mess."=20
The GOP former two-term governor spoke on the issue of California energy as=
=20
members of the Bush administration fanned out across the nation, including =
a=20
California trip by Energy Secretary Spencer Abraham, to push the White=20
House's energy policy.=20
But even the president appeared to point the finger at Wilson for some of=
=20
California's problems. "They hadn't built a power plant in 12 years" in=20
California, Bush told reporters Wednesday. "And guess what? When you grow=
=20
your state the way they have . . . it creates problems."=20
Such words chafe Wilson, who produced California Energy Commission figures=
=20
that, he said, showed that small plants were built during his administratio=
n.=20
In fact, he argued, the 1996 deregulation bill encouraged energy producers =
to=20
seek state approval for new plants.=20
While acknowledging the 1996 bill he signed was "flawed," Wilson said, "I=
=20
thought the flaws would be addressed."=20
"We knew it was not a perfect free market mechanism," said Wilson, adding=
=20
that he had strong reservations about the utility rate caps included in the=
=20
legislation. "(That) was a gamble, but it was one that paid off for while."=
=20
But, he insisted, the bill -- which critics say kicked off California's=20
energy woes -- had benefits for the state.=20
Wilson said it was believed deregulation would spur private industry to bui=
ld=20
new plants that would fuel industry and "lots of jobs for Californians."=20
Deregulation was also seen as a means to balance power companies' concerns=
=20
about a lengthy, "nightmarish" process -- which he said dated to the early=
=20
1970s -- to build large power plants.=20
Davis "is now posing in front of those plants" opening because of decisions=
=20
made before he took office, Wilson noted. "I hope that he's pleased with ou=
r=20
handiwork."=20
Wilson, also lambasted Davis for failing to heed 1998 warnings from the=20
California Energy Commission about coming blackouts.=20
And, Wilson said, as the state faced rolling blackouts, job losses, and=20
skyrocketing energy costs, Davis failed to use one of his greatest tools in=
 a=20
crisis: emergency powers.=20
Wilson noted that after the 1994 Northridge earthquake, estimates suggested=
=20
it would take 2 1/2 years to rebuild downed freeways and overpasses. He use=
d=20
his emergency powers to offer incentives to contractors that rebuilt the=20
bridges within 65 days.=20
South, noting that Davis has used his emergency powers to deal with the=20
energy crisis, said there is no comparison between an earthquake and a full=
-=20
blown statewide energy crisis.=20
