<mailto:cmarinucci@sfchronicle.com>.=20
,2001 San Francisco Chronicle </chronicle/info/copyright> Page A - 19








California buzzing with power - but for how long?=20
SAN FRANCISCO (Reuters) - Gray skies, chill fog, unseasonable rain, and=20
moderate temperatures might not make for a perfect California summer -- but=
=20
this year, it is exactly what the sun-loving state was praying for.=20
With power supplies critically short and forecasts of summer blackouts=20
swirling, California headed into the hot months geared up for repeated powe=
r=20
outages that threatened to throw the West Coast into chaos.=20
But a state that prides itself in defying prediction has done it again,=20
sailing through the first weeks of summer with so much power it is selling=
=20
its excess on the open market.=20
``Various forecasters have predicted various horror stories, and we have go=
t=20
through the summer so far without blackouts,'' said Steve Maviglio, spokesm=
an=20
for Gov. Gray Davis -- who has staked his career on beating the blackouts.=
=20
``But the situation is unpredictable, and the weather is the most=20
unpredictable thing of all.''=20
No one is saying California's energy crisis is over. The state is still=20
struggling to control the wreckage of its power deregulation scheme, a 1996=
=20
policy which was supposed to bring lower power prices and more consumer=20
choice. Instead it sparked spiraling wholesale power costs, a major utility=
=20
bankruptcy, critical power shortages, and six days of blackouts between=20
January and May.=20
The last outages swept the state May 8, unplugging tens of thousands of=20
customers in what industry experts warned was the first of as many as 260=
=20
hours of summer blackouts.=20
The absence of new blackouts has been attributed to consumer conservation=
=20
among the state's 34 million residents, improved power supplies, increased=
=20
federal price controls and above all, the unexpected blessing of a dreary=
=20
summer.=20
``Mother Nature has been very, very kind to us,'' said Severin Borenstein,=
=20
director of the University of California Energy Institute.=20
While temperatures have been several degrees lower than normal over the pas=
t=20
few days throughout California, meteorologists say the summer so far has=20
actually been marginally warmer than most.=20
But the state has so far escaped the governor's worst nightmare -- a searin=
g=20
stretch of extremely hot days that sends people running to their air=20
conditioners.=20
``Temperatures have been nominally above normal, but you haven't had a lot =
of=20
extremely hot days. If it's only moderately warm, the state can deal with=
=20
it,'' said Ed O'Lenic of the National Weather Service's Climate Prediction=
=20
Center. ''The cloudiness and the precipitation has probably helped.''=20
The cooperative weather has been matched by Californians' own conservation=
=20
efforts. Electricity use, adjusted for economic and population growth and=
=20
weather, has been falling steadily every month this year, culminating in a=
=20
12.3 percent savings in June compared with the year-ago level.=20
Conservation during the critical peak demand hours, when the threat of=20
blackouts is greatest, cut use an even more significant 14.1 percent -- a=
=20
saving of some 5,570 megawatts, or the equivalent of five big nuclear power=
=20
plants.=20
The energy picture -- further improved by three new power plants -- has=20
boosted supplies to such a degree that California recently found itself=20
selling extra power on the open market.=20
Locked in to long-term purchasing contracts and unable to store the=20
electricity, California has dumped excess power for prices far lower than i=
t=20
paid, leaving consumer groups fuming.=20
Officials dismiss the complaints as absurd, noting the amount of power=20
involved is ``inconsequential'' and stressing the entire state's power supp=
ly=20
could tip back into crisis within 24 hours of the start of a heat wave.=20
``After being blasted for blackouts, I am very happy to be criticized for=
=20
having a tiny bit too much,'' said David Freeman, Davis' chief energy=20
adviser.=20
The question now is whether California will be able to keep up its energy=
=20
balancing act for the rest of the summer.=20
The North American Electric Reliability Council (NERC), an industry group=
=20
which projected the 260 hours of blackouts this summer, has conceded those=
=20
forecasts might have been high. But it points to continued problems dogging=
=20
California's energy system including transmission bottlenecks, and inadequa=
te=20
power generation.=20
Officials and industry analysts say the biggest danger the state faces is a=
=20
sudden change in the weather, followed closely by a relaxation of consumer=
=20
conservation efforts.=20
Those worries are increased by the fact that August and September are=20
historically the hottest months across the most heavily-populated areas of=
=20
California, where late autumn heat waves are not uncommon.=20
``When we get the three-day, West-wide heat wave we are in deep trouble, an=
d=20
it is very likely we will get that sort of a heat wave at some point,''=20
Borenstein said.=20
Vancko of NERC said the current spate of good news about California's power=
=20
situation could soon be a memory. ``Nobody thinks this is more than a=20
temporary respite,'' she said. ``We may have dodged the bullet but we haven=
't=20
bitten it.''










Western Utilities Appeal To Protect Their Customers California Bail-Out by=
=20
FERC Threatens to Increase Bills for Millions of Customers=20

July 20, 2001    <JavaScript:userButton(> <JavaScript:userButton(>  BELLEVU=
E,=20
Wash.--(BUSINESS WIRE)--July 19, 2001 via NewsEdge Corporation -  West-wide=
=20
price controls on electricity implemented June 19 by the Federal Energy=20
Regulatory Commission threaten to prolong the energy crisis affecting the=
=20
West, according to petitions filed today with FERC by utilities serving=20
millions of customers.  If not revised, the price controls will quickly=20
result in higher bills for those customers.  "The FERC action in June was=
=20
focused solely on solving the immediate crisis in California," said Tim=20
Hogan, Puget Sound Energy's vice president, External Affairs. "The unintend=
ed=20
consequence is that it has aggravated the crisis for utilities and their=20
customers in surrounding states, as we experienced during the early July=20
blackouts in Nevada." In addition, one western utility, Avista Corp. of=20
Spokane, Wash., on July 18 announced a 37 percent power cost surcharge fili=
ng=20
as a direct result of the FERC price controls.  In today's FERC filing, Pug=
et=20
Sound Energy said price controls are discouraging new generating facilities=
=20
and demand-side management programs in the West, which will cause the curre=
nt=20
shortage of power to continue, resulting in extended periods of high consum=
er=20
costs. Already, more than 1,300 megawatts of planned new generation for the=
=20
region have been cancelled due to the effects of the price controls. =20
Utilities routinely sell on the wholesale market excess power and rely on=
=20
those sales to offset purchases they have to make when their customers need=
=20
additional power. The price controls, as currently structured, threaten to=
=20
force utilities to sell power at a loss, resulting in additional costs that=
=20
will have to be passed on to their customers.  "Puget Sound Energy customer=
s,=20
as well as those of other utilities, are the ones who are at risk of paying=
=20
the price for the California bail-out under the current FERC plan," Hogan=
=20
said. "Our ability to continue the successful effort to balance our energy=
=20
portfolio and keep customers' rates stable has been damaged during the rush=
=20
to solve California's problem."  PSE and other utilities filing today asked=
=20
FERC to review its June 19 order and make modifications to the price contro=
ls=20
that will not only stabilize wholesale prices in California, but also preve=
nt=20
the crisis from spreading to other states. The recommended changes would=20
allow the market to set prices that would encourage new generation and allo=
w=20
utilities to effectively manage their energy purchases and sales so their=
=20
customers would not pay higher costs.  CONTACT: Puget Sound Energy | Media=
=20
Relations | Grant Ringel, 888/831-7250 | or | Investor Relations | Julie=20
Williams, 425/462-3808








National Desk; Section A=20
Rate Proposal For Electricity In California=20

07/20/2001=20
The New York Times=20
Page 15, Column 1=20
c. 2001 New York Times Company=20
SAN FRANCISCO, July 19 -- A proposed agreement between state regulators and=
=20
the agency that buys electricity for millions of Californians would allow t=
he=20
state to raise electric rates without outside review.=20
The California Public Utilities Commission issued the agreement on Wednesda=
y=20
and it will become effective after a period for public comment in August.=
=20
The proposal explains how the commission will work with the Department of=
=20
Water Resources to ensure that the state is repaid for the billions of=20
dollars it has spent buying electricity for customers of three financially=
=20
ailing utilities.=20
In the agreement, the commission vows to assess electric rates at least=20
annually and adjust them so the department has enough money to pay for its=
=20
power purchases and administrative costs.=20
Harvey Rosenfield, the president of the Foundation for Taxpayer and Consume=
r=20
Rights, said on Wednesday that under the agreement the commission waived th=
e=20
right to deny a rate increase if it was deemed unfair to California=20
ratepayers. Mr. Rosenfield said the agreement gave unelected officials ''th=
e=20
unilateral right to order rate increases for the next 15 years.''=20
Geoff Dryvynsyde, a legal adviser at the Public Utilities Commission, said=
=20
the commission would be ''no longer in charge of determining what costs are=
=20
reasonable before it changes rates.''=20
The commission's agreement is a vital step toward California 's efforts to=
=20
issue $13 billion in bonds to recoup the more than $8 billion it has spent=
=20
since January buying electricity .=20
California wants to improve its credit rating to lower interest rates on th=
e=20
bonds and to assure Wall Street of a reliable stream of money rolling in fr=
om=20
electric rates.=20
In May, the Public Utilities Commission issued a record rate increase that=
=20
followed another January increase of roughly 10 percent.=20
The state has bought electricity for the customers of three companies since=
=20
January, when the utilities warned the state that high power prices and the=
=20
inability to recoup their costs through frozen electric rates were driving=
=20
them into bankruptcy.=20








Metro Desk=20
Edison Bailout Bills Remain Stalled
MIGUEL BUSTILLO; CARL INGRAM

07/20/2001=20
Los Angeles Times=20
Home Edition=20
Page A-25=20
Copyright 2001 / The Times Mirror Company=20
SACRAMENTO -- Leading lawmakers conceded they would probably leave on their=
=20
summer break without passing legislation aimed at rescuing Southern=20
California Edison from its financial straits as competing bailouts stalled =
in=20
the Legislature Thursday.=20
The Assembly is expected to consider one of two rival measures to save Edis=
on=20
today, and the Senate is expected to take up an Edison rescue deal of its=
=20
own.=20
But all three pending measures face long odds and none have sufficient=20
support to clear both houses, legislative leaders said.=20
With the Legislature set to quit for the summer as early as today, the=20
leaders predicted they would be forced to continue negotiations during the=
=20
monthlong recess in hopes of brokering a deal.=20
"I can't imagine that in the next 24 hours" lawmakers will reach consensus =
on=20
an Edison rescue, said Assemblyman Fred Keeley (D-Boulder Creek), who=20
coauthored one of the lower house's rescue bills with Assembly Speaker Bob=
=20
Hertzberg (D-Sherman Oaks).=20
One indication of the lack of enthusiasm for the legislation is that Keeley=
=20
himself does not support the measure that bears his name. "I don't believe=
=20
that this bill in its current form should become law," he said. "This bill =
is=20
not ready."=20
The maneuvering in both houses Thursday capped a day of frenetic activity i=
n=20
the state Capitol, which has become flooded with cell phone-carrying=20
lobbyists seeking to influence the Edison deal for seemingly every special=
=20
interest in the state.=20
Yet amid the flurry of action, there seemed little chance of actually makin=
g=20
law. Many of the participants said the legislative debate appeared to be le=
ss=20
an attempt to pass a bill than a war of one-upsmanship between the houses t=
o=20
see who could "lob a grenade" into the rival house and go home until August=
.=20
That way, if Edison soon winds up in Bankruptcy Court, leaders of each hous=
e=20
could argue they were not to blame.=20
Hoping to head off a growing sentiment among lawmakers that bankruptcy may=
=20
not be such a bad alternative, Gov. Gray Davis spent the day working the=20
phones in hopes of persuading legislators that a government rescue of Ediso=
n=20
would be good for the state.=20
To avoid mass blackouts, California has been purchasing billions of dollars=
=20
worth of electricity since the beginning of this year because the state's t=
wo=20
largest private utilities, Edison and Pacific Gas & Electric, are no longer=
=20
credit-worthy enough to buy power on behalf of their customers.=20
The utilities lost that status and ran up billions in debt the last two yea=
rs=20
because they were paying high prices for power on the wholesale market and=
=20
could not recover those costs from customers because of a state-imposed rat=
e=20
freeze.=20
As a result, the state government is stuck in the power-buying business unt=
il=20
the utilities regain their financial footing--an expensive predicament that=
=20
threatens the state's financial health.=20
Davis attempted to head off the crisis by negotiating rescues of the two=20
utilities, but PG&E lost faith in the talks and opted to take itself into=
=20
Bankruptcy Court in April, embarrassing the Democratic governor.=20
Days later, Davis reached a tentative rescue deal with Southern California=
=20
Edison. But the plan hit the Legislature with a thud amid concerns it was=
=20
overly generous to Edison, and it has languished for months.=20
Last week, lawmakers finally picked up the pace and began moving forward wi=
th=20
a series of competing proposals to alter the governor's deal with Edison. B=
ut=20
it was clear from the outset that no consensus had emerged, and many=20
lawmakers are becoming convinced that legislative inaction--even if it mean=
s=20
bankruptcy--may be the best way to resolve Edison's financial predicament.=
=20
"We're bailing out people who don't need to be bailed out," said Sen. Ross=
=20
Johnson (R-Irvine).=20
Legislative leaders hoped to pass something before today when the Assembly=
=20
and Senate are scheduled to break for their traditional summer recess. The=
=20
date is considered important because Edison and Davis had set an Aug. 15=20
deadline for lawmakers to take action on the rescue deal. If no bill is=20
passed by then--as seems likely--the utility has the right to walk away fro=
m=20
negotiations.=20
However, it became evident Thursday that the dueling measures making their=
=20
way through both houses lacked strong support.=20
In the Assembly, the Hertzberg-Keeley bill, a modification of Davis' origin=
al=20
plan, was competing against a rival bill by Assemblyman Rod Wright (D-Los=
=20
Angeles), who had teamed with Republicans to push what he bluntly called a=
=20
"straight bailout" of Edison.=20
In the Senate, Davis' original plan was amended by Sen. Byron Sher=20
(D-Stanford) and turned into a trimmed-down rescue plan that was opposed by=
=20
Edison.=20
Sher's bill was voted down twice in policy committees Wednesday and Thursda=
y,=20
but it was resuscitated both times, and is now on the Senate floor.